  <div class="answer-box">
    <span class="answer-box-label">Quick Answer</span>
    <p>A chimney should be swept <strong>at least once a year</strong> — ideally before each heating season. Heavy users, anyone burning unseasoned wood, or properties in wetter climates should sweep every season. Light users burning only well-seasoned hardwood can stretch to 18–24 months, but annual is the standard recommendation across Australia.</p>
  </div>

  <p>It's one of the most common questions a chimney sweep gets asked. The honest answer is that "once a year" is the right answer for most households — but there are real situations where that's not enough, and a few where you can safely go a little longer. This guide covers every scenario so you know exactly where you stand.</p>

  <h2>The Standard: Once a Year, Before the Heating Season</h2>

  <p>For a regularly-used fireplace or wood heater, annual sweeping is the industry standard across Australia, the UK, and North America. <strong>Australian Standard AS/NZS 2918:2018</strong> — which covers the installation of domestic solid fuel burning appliances — recommends that the flue system be inspected and cleaned at least annually. Most home insurance policies for properties with wood heaters use annual cleaning as their maintenance benchmark too.</p>

  <p>The timing matters as much as the frequency. <strong>Autumn is the ideal window</strong> — after the summer break, before you need the fire running. Booking in March, April or May means:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Any bird or possum nests built over summer are removed before you light up</li>
    <li>Creosote from the previous winter is cleared before it has another season to harden</li>
    <li>If there's a structural issue, you find out while the weather is still mild — not on the first cold night of June</li>
    <li>You avoid the autumn booking rush when every sweep in Melbourne is flat out</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How Often by Heater or Fireplace Type</h2>

  <div class="type-grid">
    <div class="type-card">
      <div class="type-card-title">🔥 Wood Heater / Slow Combustion</div>
      <div class="type-card-freq">Once a year minimum</div>
      <p>Enclosed slow combustion heaters are the most efficient but also the most prone to creosote buildup — especially if the fire is frequently run at low smoulder. Heavy users (5+ fires per week through winter) should consider every season.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="type-card">
      <div class="type-card-title">🧱 Open Brick Fireplace</div>
      <div class="type-card-freq">Once a year</div>
      <p>Open fireplaces burn less efficiently than enclosed heaters, meaning more soot and creosote per fire. Annual sweeping is essential. The masonry also needs to be checked — mortar deteriorates over time and older chimneys are prone to cracking.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="type-card">
      <div class="type-card-title">🏕️ Fireplace Insert</div>
      <div class="type-card-freq">Once a year</div>
      <p>Inserts share the same flue as the original masonry chimney but burn more like a wood heater. The connection point between the insert and the flue liner is a common area for creosote accumulation and needs annual attention.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="type-card">
      <div class="type-card-title">⛽ Gas Fireplace / Log Fire</div>
      <div class="type-card-freq">Every 2 years / as needed</div>
      <p>Gas appliances don't produce creosote but the flue can still collect debris and the burner and seals need periodic inspection. Every two years is a reasonable guide, or annually if it's a heavily used appliance.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

