  <h2>When Once a Year Isn't Enough</h2>

  <h3>You're burning a lot of wood</h3>
  <p>A household running the fire five or six nights a week from May through September is generating considerably more creosote than one using it occasionally. If you're burning 3 or more trailer loads of wood per winter, consider getting the flue checked mid-season as well as before it starts. The cost of an extra clean is far less than a chimney fire.</p>

  <h3>You've been burning unseasoned or green wood</h3>
  <p>This is the single biggest driver of excessive creosote. Freshly cut or poorly dried wood contains high moisture content — it burns cooler and produces thick, sticky creosote that coats the flue walls much faster than properly seasoned hardwood. If you've been burning green wood, you likely need a clean after a single winter regardless of when the last one was done.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>Properly seasoned firewood has a moisture content below 20%. Wood sold as "firewood" isn't always properly dried — especially if it was cut recently. Split wood needs at least 12 months of covered, ventilated storage before it's ready to burn efficiently.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>You frequently run the fire low or smoulder overnight</h3>
  <p>Slow combustion heaters are designed to be run hot — around 150–200°C at the flue outlet. When the fire is damped down to a slow smoulder, the flue temperature drops and moisture and tar condense out of the smoke onto the liner. People who regularly bank the fire down overnight are accelerating their creosote buildup significantly.</p>

  <h3>You live in the Dandenong Ranges or Yarra Valley</h3>
  <p>The Dandenong Ranges receive up to 1,400mm of rainfall per year in some areas — one of the wettest parts of Victoria. The persistent ambient moisture, combined with the tendency to burn locally-sourced wood that may not be fully seasoned, means flues in this area accumulate creosote faster than in drier Melbourne suburbs. Annual cleaning here should be treated as a firm rule rather than a rough guide.</p>

  <h2>Holiday Homes and Weekender Properties</h2>

  <p>Many people assume a holiday home chimney needs less frequent cleaning because it gets fewer fires. The opposite is often true. Irregular use — heavy for a week over winter, then idle for months — is actually one of the harder patterns on a flue:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>The flue never fully warms up from cold, so condensation and creosote form more readily in the first few fires of each visit</li>
    <li>Idle periods allow moisture and wildlife access — bird nests and debris are common in properties that sit empty for extended periods</li>
    <li>Owners aren't present to notice early warning signs like smoke spillage or deteriorating performance</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Annual cleaning is the right call for holiday homes, even if the total number of fires per year is relatively low.</p>

  <h2>Just Moved Into a Property? Do This First</h2>

  <p>If you've just bought or rented a home with a fireplace or wood heater, <strong>get the chimney inspected before you use it</strong> — regardless of when it was last cleaned or what the previous owners say. A standard building inspection doesn't include a proper chimney assessment. What can be missed without looking up the flue:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Bird or possum nests blocking the upper flue</li>
    <li>Heavy creosote deposits from years of unseasoned wood use</li>
    <li>Cracked flue liner or damaged mortar joints</li>
    <li>Missing or damaged flue cap</li>
    <li>Debris from roof work or renovation</li>
  </ul>
  <p>None of these are visible from the firebox. A sweep before first use is cheap insurance.</p>

  <h2>Signs Your Chimney Needs Sweeping Now — Regardless of Schedule</h2>

  <p>These are the warning signs that mean you should book immediately, not wait for your annual clean:</p>

  <ul class="sign-list">
    <li><strong>Smoke coming back into the room</strong> — the most obvious sign of a blocked, restricted or damaged flue</li>
    <li><strong>Persistent smoky smell when the fire is off</strong> — creosote deposits or old ash holding odour in the flue</li>
    <li><strong>Fire difficult to start or won't stay alight</strong> — restricted airflow from buildup or blockage</li>
    <li><strong>Glass on the wood heater door going heavily black</strong> — indicates incomplete combustion, often from creosote-narrowed flue or wet wood</li>
    <li><strong>Visible soot or debris falling into the firebox</strong> — a sign of loose deposits, possible nesting material, or structural movement</li>
    <li><strong>Rumbling or roaring sound from the chimney</strong> — this can indicate a chimney fire and requires immediate action</li>
    <li><strong>Fire hasn't been used in over a year</strong> — inspect before lighting again, especially if you're in a tree-lined area</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="warning-box">
    <div class="warning-box-icon">🔴</div>
    <div class="warning-box-body"><strong>If you hear a roaring or rumbling sound from your chimney while a fire is burning, extinguish the fire immediately and call 000.</strong> This is a likely chimney fire — burning creosote deposits inside the flue. Don't use the fireplace until a sweep has inspected the full system for damage.</div>
  </div>

  <h2>What Happens If You Don't Sweep Regularly?</h2>

  <p>Skipping annual sweeping isn't just an inconvenience — the risks are real and escalating:</p>

  <p><strong>Chimney fire.</strong> Creosote is highly flammable. As it builds up on the flue walls, the risk of it igniting from a hot flue gas increases sharply. A chimney fire can reach temperatures above 1,000°C — hot enough to crack the flue liner, damage the masonry, and ignite nearby timbers. Many house fires originate in the chimney.</p>

  <p><strong>Carbon monoxide risk.</strong> A blocked or deteriorating flue can force combustion gases — including carbon monoxide — back into the living space. CO is colourless and odourless and can be fatal. Restricted airflow from creosote buildup is one of the most common causes of CO incidents in homes with wood heaters.</p>

  <p><strong>Insurance issues.</strong> If a chimney fire or CO incident occurs and you can't demonstrate regular maintenance, your insurer may refuse or reduce your claim. Annual sweeping creates a clear maintenance record.</p>

  <p><strong>Structural deterioration.</strong> Acidic combustion byproducts attack mortar and flue liners over time. Catching deterioration early — at the annual clean — is far cheaper than a full flue reline or chimney rebuild.</p>

