    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How often should a wood heater flue be cleaned?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">A wood heater flue should be cleaned once a year at minimum. Slow combustion heaters used regularly through winter accumulate creosote quickly — especially if the fire is frequently smouldered at low temperatures rather than run hot. If you use your wood heater more than 3–4 times per week throughout winter, consider cleaning every season.</div>
    </details>
    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Does a chimney need sweeping if I barely use it?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Yes. Even a rarely-used chimney should be inspected every one to two years. Bird nests, possum activity, debris and moisture damage can block or deteriorate a flue even when it's not being used. If the fireplace has sat idle for 12 or more months, have it checked before the next fire.</div>
    </details>
    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How often for a holiday home or short-stay rental?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Once a year — the same as a main residence. Irregular use (heavy for short stays, then idle for months) is actually harder on a flue than regular consistent use, because the system never properly warms up and creosote condenses more readily. Annual cleaning is important even if the total number of fires per year is modest.</div>
    </details>
    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Does burning unseasoned wood mean I need to sweep more often?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Yes, significantly. Unseasoned or green wood contains high moisture and burns cooler, producing far more creosote than properly dried hardwood. If you've been regularly burning unseasoned wood, your flue could need cleaning after a single season. Switch to properly seasoned hardwood (moisture content below 20%) and you'll notice cleaner glass, better draw, and less frequent cleaning needed.</div>
    </details>
    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>What does Australian Standard AS/NZS 2918 say?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Australian Standard AS/NZS 2918:2018 (Domestic solid fuel burning appliances — Installation) recommends that solid fuel heating appliances and their flue systems be inspected and cleaned at least annually. Most home insurance policies for properties with wood heaters also require evidence of regular maintenance — annual cleaning is the standard benchmark.</div>
    </details>
    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>What time of year should I get my chimney swept?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Autumn is the ideal time — March, April or May in Victoria. This is before the heating season starts, after any summer bird nesting activity, and before the autumn booking rush when chimney sweeps fill up fast. Getting it done in autumn means your fire is ready to use the moment you need it.</div>
    </details>
    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How long does a chimney sweep take?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Most jobs take 45–75 minutes depending on the system type and how much buildup there is. A standard flue and wood heater clean is typically around 45–60 minutes. A masonry brick chimney with a deep smoke chamber can take up to 90 minutes if it hasn't been done in several years.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

